DOMAIN_OVERVIEW:
This domain covers the thematic core of Habermas' engagement with Weber: his
reconstruction of Weber's multi-dimensional theory of rationalization into the
framework of communicative versus strategic/instrumental reason. Weber diagnosed
Western modernity through the twin concepts of formal rationalization
(the increasing dominance of means-end calculation in law, economy, and
administration) and disenchantment (Entzauberung -- the retreat of magic,
religion, and ultimate meaning from the public world). These processes were
linked in Weber's Protestant Ethic thesis, which traced the elective affinity
between the inner-worldly asceticism of Calvinist Protestantism and the spirit
of capitalism. Weber saw the outcome as the "iron cage" of bureaucratic
rationality that threatened to trap modernity in purposive-rational action,
producing both loss of freedom and loss of meaning.

Habermas accepts much of this diagnosis while fundamentally reconstructing its
conceptual foundations. In The Theory of Communicative Action (TCA), he argues
that Weber conflates two distinct dimensions of rationalization: the
rationalization of worldviews (which opens up the communicative potential of
language through differentiation of validity claims) and the institutional
rationalization of action in social subsystems. Habermas' "selective
rationalization thesis" holds that capitalist modernization has developed the
system dimension (market, bureaucracy) while suppressing the communicative
rationalization of the lifeworld. The colonization of the lifeworld -- where
system imperatives penetrate and distort communicative action -- then becomes
Habermas' reformulation of Weber's iron cage. Critics argue that Habermas
"domesticates" Weber's tragic account of disenchantment by treating it as
merely a pathological deviation from an available communicative rationality,
whereas Weber saw the conflict between the value spheres (and the loss of
religious meaning) as genuinely irresolvable.

The secondary literature falls into three main groups: (1) commentaries on TCA
that trace Habermas' reconstruction of Weber in detail (McCarthy, Ingram,
Honneth and Joas); (2) comparisons that highlight what Habermas preserves versus
distorts in Weber (Breen, Dahms, Bowring); and (3) work on Weber's concepts
of disenchantment and rationalization that provides the backdrop against which
Habermas' reception is evaluated (Carroll, Etzrodt, Kalberg, Schluchter, Green).

RELEVANCE_TO_PROJECT:
The selective rationalization thesis and the colonization of the lifeworld are
the two moments through which Habermas most directly inherits and transforms
Weber's substantive social theory. This domain provides the conceptual vocabulary
for evaluating whether Habermas productively extends or fundamentally distorts
Weber's account of Western rationalization and its pathologies.

