  literature (including Habermas' reception) has overemphasized it. He proposes
  a more analytically precise vocabulary distinguishing de-magification,
  Hegelian alienation, Marxist alienation, and Durkheimian anomie to describe
  the different rationalization processes Weber identifies in Economy and Society
  and his historical studies. In the economic-political sphere, rationalization
  is best characterized as Marxist alienation; in the religious sphere, as
  de-magification and Hegelian alienation.

  RELEVANCE: The most recent (2024) substantial treatment of Weber's
  rationalization concepts and their implications for Habermas' reception.
  Directly addresses whether Habermas' reading of disenchantment as the central
  theme of Weber's rationalization thesis is adequate, suggesting that Habermas
  may be interpreting Weber through an overly unified conceptual lens.

  POSITION: Analytical disaggregation of Weber's rationalization processes,
  questioning the primacy of disenchantment as a master concept.
  },
  keywords = {disenchantment, rationalization, Weber, alienation, anomie, Medium}
}

